d boyars reviewed their medical histories, evaluated their spiritual qualities, noted their physical appearances, and confirmed their virtue. Those who passed muster were presented to the tsar, who inspected the candidates one by one—usually without speaking to any of them—and chose one to be immediately escorted to the Kremlin to prepare for her wedding and new life as the tsar's consort.Alongside accounts of sordid boyar plots against brides, the multiple marriages of Ivan the Terrible, and the fascinating spectacle of the bride-show ritual, A Bride for the Tsar offers an analysis of the show's role in the complex politics of royal marriage in early modern Russia. Russell E. Martin argues that the nature of the rituals surrounding the selection of a bride for the tsar tells us much about the extent of his power, revealing it to be limited and collaborative, not autocratic. Extracting the bride-show from relative obscurity, Martin persuasively establishes it as an essential element of the tsarist political system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMarriage customs and riteszRussiaxHistoryy16th century. 0aMarriage customs and riteszRussiaxHistoryy17th century. 0aMarriages of royalty and nobilityxPolitical aspectszRussia. 0aMarriages of royalty and nobilityzRussiaxHistoryy16th century. 0aMarriages of royalty and nobilityzRussiaxHistoryy17th century. 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aRussian aristocracy, Tsar's consort, politics of royal marriage, tasrist political system.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175665840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501756658423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/978